node.text:
The Frick’s temporary move to Frick Madison has prompted new ways of looking at our works of art. The reframing of the collection sheds light on the fact that the Frick's art, although predominantly European, is undeniably linked to the world beyond Europe. In this new series, we’re exploring some of these stories, asking "where in the world" we can find new connections to familiar objects. 🗺️

In the inaugural episode, Curator Aimee Ng explores the history of mahogany, a material hidden beneath the surface of a Rembrandt portrait and sourced oceans away from the famed artist's homeland.

In this video filmed in the 2019 exhibition "Henry Arnhold’s Meissen Palace: Celebrating a Collector," Paul Arnhold (@paularnhold) speaks to the legacy of his grandfather’s collection.

node.text: This year commemorates the one-hundredth anniversary of women’s right to vote in the United States. The Frick Collection is celebrating with a series that honors the stories of women who shaped the Frick. In the last episode, meet Elsie de Wolfe, America's first professional interior designer, who decorated fourteen rooms in the Frick's Fifth Avenue home.

node.title: Elsie de Wolfe • What's Her Story?

The year 2020 marks the one-hundredth anniversary of the ratification of the 19th Amendment, which granted millions of women in the U.S. the right to vote. In celebration of this landmark occasion, the Frick is highlighting stories of women who made, appear in, collected, and took care of art in our collection in an online mini-series.

Curator Aimee Ng is continuing the series with a look at a portrait of Miss Mary Edwards, a woman who took her life and legacy into her own hands. #WhatsHerStory

node.text:
Today marks the one-hundredth anniversary of women's right to vote across the United States. This year, in celebration of this landmark occasion, the Frick is highlighting stories of women who made, appear in, collected, and took care of our collection in an online mini-series. These stories also remind us of the many thousands of women who had to fight for their right to vote until the Voting Rights Act of 1965 and beyond, even today.

Curator Aimee Ng is continuing the series with a look at Helen Clay Frick, the founder and first director of the Frick Art Reference Library and an instrumental force in The Frick Collection's early art acquisitions. #WhatsHerStory

node.title: Helen Clay Frick  What's Her Story?

node.text:
This year is the one-hundredth anniversary of women's right to vote in the United States. The Frick is celebrating by spotlighting the oft-overlooked stories of women who made, appeared in, collected, or took care of our collection.

Before the Frick opened as a museum, it was a sizably staffed home. Curator Aimee Ng and Associate Museum Educator Caitlin Henningsen continue the series with the story of Ruth Berlin, one of the Frick family's twenty-odd domestic workers. A Swedish immigrant, Ruth Berlin worked as a chambermaid at 1 East 70th Street from 1921 to 1925. #WhatsHerStory

node.text:
#Vermeer's "Mistress and Maid" hasn't always been at the Frick. Perhaps more surprising is that it's had at least fifteen different owners and traveled over 8,300 miles (or a third of the way around the world) in its 354-year existence.

🗺️ Trace the painting's journey, from the artist's home in Delft through its recent installation at #FrickMadison, with a new interactive map on the blog (link in bio).
—
Installation view at Frick Madison of Vermeer's Mistress and Maid, The Frick Collection, New York. Photo: Joseph Coscia Jr., 2021

node.accessibility_caption: Clock consisting of a gilt-bronze lion holding up a dial, placed on an ebony and wood base.

node.text:
It's #WorldLionDay. This extraordinary sculptural clock is an automaton: When wound, the lion's eyes flick from side to side with each tick 👀 and its jaw opens when the clock chimes.
—

Now you see him, now you don't.🪄

It's not magic, it's the afterlife of one sixteenth-century painting currently in the collection of the @mfahouston. The work was modified by a Berlin dealer in the early twentieth century, and the #FrickPhotoarchive holds photographs of it from intermittent moments in the last century, allowing us to peek at its past states.
 
Head to our #PhotoarchiveFinds Highlights for the complete surprising story, uncovered by the #FrickLibrary's team of Photoarchivists. 
—
Photographic reproduction of Jan Gossaert (1478–1532), The Holy Family, early 16th century. Frick Digital Collections, Frick Art Reference Library

Jesus is seen lying to the right of the scene, holes are evident in his hands and right foot, a cloth billows behind him and Mary stands upright to the left, with her arms outstretched at both sides. She holds the piece of cloth at the top of Jesus's head with her left hand.

node.text:
Italian Baroque sculptor Alessandro Algardi was born #onthisday in 1598.

In his bronze "Pietà," the artist activates a small space with dynamic motion: Mary's arm juts out beyond the bronze surface in a gesture of despair as she lifts the expressively draped shroud covering her son. The lyrical drama of the moment is characteristic of Algardi's sculptural style.
—
Alessandro Algardi (Italian, 1598–1654), Pietà, ca. 1630. Bronze, 12 3/4 x 12 1/8 in. (32.4 x 30.8 cm). The #FrickCollection, New York
